# Bootstrap your node

Recall that any computer that's managed by a Chef server is called a _node_. We call the process that installs the Chef tools on a node and the initial check-in to the Chef server _bootstrapping_ the node.

Let's bootstrap a node and execute the web server cookbook on it.

If you haven't set up a Chef server and uploaded your cookbook to it, the [previous lesson](/windows/get-ready-to-add-another-server/) shows you how.

## <i class="fa fa-windows" style="margin-right:3px;"></i> Get a Windows Server machine to bootstrap

In the previous tutorials, you configured the server directly. The machine you used had the Chef tools pre-installed. Now you need to get a machine that doesn't have the Chef tools on it so you can see how the bootstrap process works.

Like the previous tutorials, there are two ways to get set up.

Option 1: use your own machine. Any Windows Server machine that meets the [system requirements](http://docs.getchef.com/chef_system_requirements.html) works great. Don't install the Chef tools on it just yet.

